[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    13[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThis is the densest patient-safety writing in the cookbook to date and the strongest fourth recipe in the Anomaly Detection chapter. The Saturday-night vignette (overnight pharmacist covering two buildings, queue of forty-three orders, the vancomycin 2 grams q8h order on a 52 kg step-down patient that gets corrected to 1 gram q12h before the first dose leaves the Pyxis) lands the operational reality in three paragraphs. The contrast vignette (600-bed academic hospital at 3:15 a.m., the same alert firing on 40% of vancomycin orders, the eleven-hour-into-twelve-hour-shift pharmacist clicking through, the dialysis consult thirty-six hours later) makes the alert-fatigue framing visceral. The five-flavors-of-anomaly taxonomy (dose, frequency-and-duration, interaction, controlled-substance pattern, aggregate-and-trend) is the right teaching anchor for this domain because each flavor has structurally different data, model, and workflow requirements, and the recipe is explicit about it. The seven concrete texture examples (pediatric amoxicillin 35.7 mg/kg, the 83-year-old on warfarin/apixaban/aspirin with recent GI bleed, the ICU insulin trajectory drifting from 2 to 14 U/hr, the post-op morphine pattern that's inconsistent with pain trajectory, the pharmacy technician with seven of twelve restock discrepancies, the home-delivery patient escalating from 90/60 days to 45 days to 30 days) each map to a real medication-safety failure mode any pharmacy informatics director would recognize.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    14[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    15[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe "asymmetry between false positives and false negatives is enormous, and it should shape every architectural choice in the pipeline" framing at the head of The Problem section is publication-ready voice on the design constraint that drives this domain. The reference-data subsection naming First Databank, Wolters Kluwer, Micromedex, Lexicomp, Medi-Span (all real commercial drug knowledge bases) plus the open-source path through RxNorm, DailyMed, OpenFDA is the right discipline. The patient-context-cache subsection identifying weight, eGFR, active medications, active diagnoses, recent labs, allergies, and acuity as the minimum context bar is operationally accurate, and the staleness framing ("a 30-day-old weight on an ICU patient is useless") is the kind of detail-level teaching the cookbook is built on. The clinical-baselines-vs-statistical-baselines subsection's hybrid framing (rules layer for unambiguous high-severity errors, population-level for high-volume drugs, patient-level for trajectory work) is the architecturally correct factoring. The statistical-methods progression (rule-based screening → z-scores → CUSUM/EWMA → Isolation Forest → supervised classifiers → LLM clinical reasoning → graph analytics for diversion) is the right pedagogical order, and the closing posture ("Don't skip the rules layer in favor of starting with ML") is operationally correct. The alert-fatigue subsection is the most substantive treatment of this constraint in the cookbook so far, and "the clinician who's been trained to ignore the system is less safe than they'd be with no system at all" is publication-ready voice on the most consequential clinical-informatics failure mode.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    16[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    17[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe hybrid streaming-plus-batch architecture (real-time path for order verification and cabinet pull, batch pattern path for trajectory and population-level work, dedicated diversion path for controlled substances, severity tiering driving routing into interrupt vs synchronous vs background queues, feedback capture closing the loop into rule tuning and supervised retraining) is the architecturally correct factoring for this problem class. The "interrupt severity is reserved for events where the risk of dispensing is high and the cost of interruption is acceptable" framing on severity tiering is the operationally correct backstop on the alert-fatigue problem.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    18[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    19[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe Honest Take is publication-ready and should be preserved verbatim. The seven lessons (rules layer is not a stepping stone to be replaced by ML, alert-fatigue math is harsher than you think, patient-context cache is the real hard part, diversion detection module is politically sensitive in ways the technical design doesn't capture, trajectory detection pays off in unexpected ways, the oncology context flag was the most valuable feature engineering, the explainability work should drive modeling choices not the other way around) land the right teaching priorities. The closing trap warning ("do not let the business case be 'reduce adverse drug events by X%' ... frame it as clinician-endorsed utility, and the metrics align with the clinical goal") is the kind of authentic operations-engineer voice that distinguishes the cookbook.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    20[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    21[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mStyle hygiene is exceptionally clean. Zero em dashes (direct U+2014 character check across the file: zero matches). No marketing language ("leverage," "seamless," "unlock," "empower," "revolutionize" all absent; one occurrence of "transforms" in a technical context describing event normalization, not marketing usage). No documentation-voice. The 70/30 vendor balance is preserved cleanly: the conceptual sections (Problem, Technology, General Architecture Pattern) are vendor-neutral and a reader on GCP or Azure could substitute their cloud's primitives without rewriting any of the teaching; AWS service names enter at the AWS Implementation section and stay there. HTML-comment TODOs (eight total) are all forward-placeholder for industry-source verification (alert override rates, ADE cost estimates, FDA CDS guidance reference, validated LLM clinical-reasoning patterns, aws-samples and AWS blog post citations) and are the chapter-2-and-3-settled posture.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    22[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    23[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe findings cluster around recurring chapter patterns and a small number of domain-accuracy gaps. There are no CRITICAL findings and no HIGH findings. The MEDIUM cluster includes outcome-event idempotency at the EventBridge → feedback-capture Lambda path (recurring trigger-idempotency pattern across Recipes 2.4-2.10, 3.1, 3.2, and 3.3, surfacing here for the tenth consecutive time); no DLQ or poison-message handling for the real-time-anomaly-service, event-normalizer, or feedback-capture Lambdas (architecturally critical for a patient-safety system where a dropped event is a missed flag); SNS interrupt-alert payload PHI minimization not explicitly specified in the pseudocode (the chapter-3-settled "event-id-only" convention from Recipes 3.1 and 3.3 is implied via the Python companion but not stated in the main recipe); subgroup-data governance for fairness monitoring acknowledged in prose but the architectural artifacts that make subgroup monitoring binding are not specified (same finding shape as Recipes 3.2 S2 and 3.3 S2); the oncology-protocol context flag identified in The Honest Take as "the most valuable feature-engineering work" is not specified architecturally (no data-flow, no source-of-truth, no retention or audit framing); the cross-reactive-allergy default severity comment in the rule-screen pseudocode ([38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140m"almost always interrupt-severity"[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m) overstates the appropriate severity tier for modern penicillin-cephalosporin cross-reactivity rates and risks teaching readers to over-restrict beta-lactam therapy.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    24[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    25[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mLOW findings are operational and editorial polish: VPC endpoint precision (CloudWatch monitoring vs Logs, EventBridge events vs Scheduler, SageMaker api/runtime/featurestore-runtime distinction, SNS, Step Functions, Neptune, MSK/MQ); VPC Flow Logs not explicitly required; sample timestamps use future dates; the diversion alert sample uses an "investigation" severity tier that doesn't appear in the severity hierarchy defined elsewhere; HL7 v2 MLLP bridge security posture (Site-to-Site VPN vs Direct Connect) not addressed; the amoxicillin 15 mg/kg per dose threshold in the Expected Results sample reflects standard-dose AOM (40-50 mg/kg/day TID), not current AAP high-dose AOM guidance (80-90 mg/kg/day BID), without an indication-aware caveat.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    26[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
