[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    29[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThe risk profile is the highest in Chapter 3 to date. Unlike Recipes 3.1, 3.2, and 3.3 (financial-and-operational stakes, no patient-harm path), Recipe 3.4 is in the medication-dispensing path and a missed flag can produce direct patient harm (AKI, dialysis, sentinel event, death). The recipe correctly addresses this in the FP/FN asymmetry framing, the alert-fatigue subsection, the "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" disaster-recovery and graceful-degradation discussion, and the regulatory-alignment paragraph naming FDA CDS Software guidance, state pharmacy boards, Joint Commission, and DEA. The fairness surface area is also distinctive: the recipe correctly identifies that medication-dosing models trained on majority populations may flag legitimate dosing for underrepresented populations as anomalous, that pain-management alerts can align with known racial disparities in opioid prescribing, and that subgroup monitoring is "part of the minimum deployment, not optional." The architectural artifacts that make subgroup monitoring binding rather than aspirational are S2's concern.[K
