[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    132[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;143;161;179m###[38;2;192;197;206m [38;2;143;161;179mArchitecture Expert Review[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    133[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    134[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;143;161;179m####[38;2;192;197;206m [38;2;143;161;179mWhat's Done Well[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    135[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    136[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe hybrid streaming-plus-batch architecture (real-time path for order verification and cabinet pull, batch pattern path for trajectory and population-level work, dedicated diversion path for controlled substances, severity tiering driving routing into interrupt vs synchronous vs background queues, feedback capture closing the loop) is the architecturally correct factoring for this problem class. The decision to run different paths at different latency regimes is the architectural reframe most first-time builders miss, and the recipe is explicit about it ("the architecture is a hybrid of streaming and batch, with a shared feature and reference-data layer underneath").[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    137[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The five-flavors-of-anomaly taxonomy (dose, frequency-and-duration, interaction, controlled-substance pattern, aggregate-and-trend) is the right teaching anchor for designing the pipeline. The closing posture ("A useful first version picks one or two classes, does them well, and earns the right to expand. Most organizations start with dose anomalies (highest safety impact per alert) or controlled-substance patterns (highest regulatory exposure)") is the operationally correct prioritization.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    138[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The hybrid clinical-baselines-vs-statistical-baselines framing (rules layer for unambiguous errors, population-level z-scores for common drugs with stable distributions, patient-level baselines for trajectory work, with rules as backstop) is the architecturally correct factoring. The "Don't skip the rules layer in favor of starting with ML: rules catch the highest-severity errors with the highest explainability, and they form the backstop that the ML layer depends on" closing posture is the right teaching for a domain where teams tend to over-engineer.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    139[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Reference-data versioning is named explicitly: "Store the version of the knowledge base used at the time of each alert, because when an alert is audited ('why did we flag this?'), reproducing the decision requires knowing which reference data was in force." This is the discipline most first-time builders skip and then fail to satisfy a Joint Commission or DEA audit. The Python companion implements this correctly (per the existing code review).[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    140[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The patient-context-cache architectural pattern (read-optimized DynamoDB store, refreshed from EHR events, with staleness flags per field) is the right factoring for the latency budget. The "Query latency matters: every dispense event checks the cache, and a slow cache turns a 50-millisecond dispense check into a several-second delay that clinicians will not tolerate" framing is operationally accurate.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    141[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Severity tiering as a first-class architectural concern (interrupt, synchronous, background) with the explicit operational distinction is the architecturally correct factoring. "'Interrupt' is reserved for events where the risk of dispensing is high and the cost of interruption is acceptable" plus "The tier thresholds are set by clinical leadership, monitored against override rates, and revised regularly based on feedback data" is the right governance posture.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    142[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Feedback capture and retraining as architectural concerns (override reasons with structured codes, ADE linkage to dispense records, monthly or quarterly cadence, override-rate-driven rule retirement) is the right factoring. The closing observation that the missed-event signal is "the most important input and the hardest to act on, because by definition you don't know what you missed" is publication-ready voice on the central feedback-loop discipline of this domain.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    143[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The Step 7 missed-adverse-event handling is the most-developed feedback-loop pattern in the cookbook. The pseudocode explicitly handles the false-negative case (an ADE happened, the system did NOT flag it) by emitting both a [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mmissed_adverse_event[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m metric and a [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mMedicationAnomaly.MissedEvent[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;191;97;106m EventBridge event for clinical-informatics review. This is the architectural primitive that distinguishes a patient-safety system from a generic anomaly detector.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    144[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m The "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" section is dense and architecturally substantive: clinical rule authoring as a program, drug reference content licensing and integration, HL7/FHIR integration as a team sport, real-time latency budget, graceful degradation when dependencies fail, feedback capture for busy clinicians, severity tiering governance, diversion investigation legal complexity, bias and equity monitoring, regulatory and accreditation alignment, data retention and audit trail integrity, disaster recovery and business continuity. Twelve substantive bullets each tied to a real production concern.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    145[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Cost estimate is defensible and correctly framed against the cost-avoidance of preventable ADEs. "Total infrastructure: typically $1,500-4,000/month for a mid-size hospital. Compare to cost avoidance: the average preventable ADE costs roughly $5,000-$10,000 per event in additional care, and sentinel-event-level harms cost far more." The HTML-comment TODO acknowledging that current AHRQ/ISMP/IHI ADE cost estimates need verification before citing specifics is the right discipline.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    146[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m Implementation-time tiers (4-6 months Basic, 9-15 months Production-ready, 12-24 months for variations) are realistic and resist optimism bias. Most first-time builders underestimate this; the recipe doesn't.[K
