[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    299[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mLocation:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Why-These-Services AWS Lambda paragraph ("The hot path (rule screening, cache lookup, z-score computation) needs to complete in tens to low hundreds of milliseconds"); General Architecture Pattern Real-time path subsection ("The latency budget is on the order of tens to low hundreds of milliseconds end-to-end"); "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" Real-time latency budget paragraph ("A well-designed system targets p95 under 500ms end-to-end").[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    300[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mProblem:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Three different latency budgets are quoted across the recipe. The Why-These-Services and General Architecture sections claim "tens to low hundreds of milliseconds" for the hot path. The "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" section says "A well-designed system targets p95 under 500ms end-to-end." These are roughly compatible (the Lambda hot path can be 100-200ms while the end-to-end including upstream message delivery and downstream UX rendering is 500ms), but the recipe doesn't make the distinction explicit, and a reader budgeting their architecture against the "tens to low hundreds of milliseconds" target will be surprised when the end-to-end p95 lands at 500ms.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    301[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    302[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m  [38;2;191;97;106mAdditionally, the hot path as specified does multiple sequential remote calls (DynamoDB GetItem on patient-context-cache, SageMaker Feature Store GetRecord on baselines, S3 GetObject on clinical rules, EventBridge PutEvent on output, OpenSearch Index on audit). At realistic per-call latencies (1-10ms each for cache hits, 20-50ms for first-time S3 reads, 5-10ms for EventBridge), the cumulative single-event latency can reach 100-200ms even on the happy path. The "tens to low hundreds of milliseconds" framing is achievable but tight, and the recipe should say so.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    303[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mFix:[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;191;97;106m Reconcile the latency-budget framings into a single coherent picture: "The hot-path Lambda (cache lookup + rule screen + z-score check + EventBridge PutEvent) targets p95 of 100-200ms; the end-to-end latency from order verification UI to flag arrival in the pharmacist's UI targets p95 under 500ms (the additional 300-400ms accounts for upstream message delivery, downstream UX rendering, and the alert-routing Lambda). For the Pyxis or Omnicell cabinet-pull experience the end-to-end target is sub-second because the cabinet door has to open before the user perceives a delay; this is the tightest budget in the architecture and may require provisioned concurrency on the hot-path Lambda and a co-located (regional) cache rather than the cross-region default."[K
