[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    528[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThere are zero HIGH findings. The MEDIUM findings cluster across architectural completeness (A1 idempotency, A2 DLQs, A3 oncology-protocol gap, A4 cross-reactivity calibration), security (S1 SNS minimization, S2 subgroup governance, S5 per-consumer IAM), and the LOW findings cover operational and editorial polish. The single most-consequential fix is A3 (oncology-protocol context flag) because The Honest Take section identifies it as the highest-value feature-engineering work in the recipe and the pseudocode doesn't reflect it.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    529[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    530[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mFinding A1 is the now-recurring trigger-idempotency pattern, surfacing for the tenth consecutive recipe (2.4-2.10, 3.1, 3.2, 3.3, 3.4). The cookbook would benefit substantially from a shared appendix that covers the patterns once (S3 events with conditional DynamoDB writes, EventBridge bus → Lambda async with deterministic event keys, EventBridge Scheduler with deterministic Step Functions execution names, Kinesis with idempotent consumers, SQS with deduplication tokens). Each subsequent recipe could reference the appendix rather than repeat the discipline. With the per-recipe-edit posture producing diminishing returns, the trigger-idempotency appendix is the highest-leverage cookbook-wide editorial investment.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    531[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    532[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mFinding A2 (DLQs) is operationally critical for this recipe specifically because of the patient-safety stakes. For Recipes 3.1, 3.2, 3.3 a dropped event is an operational concern; for Recipe 3.4 a dropped real-time event is a dispense without an anomaly check, which is precisely the failure mode the entire pipeline is designed to prevent. The DLQ-depth alarm threshold for the real-time path should be 1 (single-event sensitivity), not the typical "alert on sustained backlog" pattern.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    533[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    534[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mFinding S1 is the now-recurring PHI-minimization-inside-the-BAA pattern, with the fifth distinct surface across the cookbook (Chapter 2: serialized prompt context; Recipe 3.1: examiner free-text reasoning; Recipe 3.2: patient-facing reminder content for high-stigma specialties; Recipe 3.3: internal SNS notification payload between system components; Recipe 3.4: SNS interrupt-alert payload to pharmacist with high-stigma drug-class disclosure). A cookbook-wide PHI-minimization appendix would consolidate all five surfaces with one teaching pass.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    535[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    536[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe Honest Take section is publication-ready and should be preserved verbatim. The seven-paragraph structure (rules layer is not a stepping stone, alert fatigue math is harsher than you think, patient-context cache is the real hard part, diversion detection is politically sensitive, trajectory detection pays off in unexpected ways, oncology context flag was the most valuable feature engineering, explainability work should drive modeling choices) is the kind of operations-engineer voice the cookbook is built on. The closing trap warning ("do not let the business case be 'reduce adverse drug events by X%' ... Frame it as clinician-endorsed utility, and the metrics align with the clinical goal") is the kind of authentic operations-engineer voice that distinguishes the cookbook.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    537[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    538[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe Saturday-night-vs-academic-hospital vignette is the densest patient-safety writing in the cookbook to date and should not be shortened. The community-hospital save (the pharmacist's mental math catching the vancomycin overdose) and the academic-hospital miss (the same training in a different alert-saturation environment, dialysis consult thirty-six hours later) is the densest alert-fatigue framing in the cookbook. Each of the seven concrete texture examples (pediatric amoxicillin, the 83-year-old on triple anticoagulation, the ICU insulin trajectory, the post-op morphine pattern, the pharmacy technician restock cluster, the home-delivery refill escalation, the controlled-substance graph) maps to a real medication-safety scenario that any pharmacy informatics director would recognize.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    539[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    540[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe five-flavors-of-anomaly taxonomy is the right teaching anchor and is operationally accurate. The recipe's prioritization guidance ("Most organizations start with dose anomalies (highest safety impact per alert) or controlled-substance patterns (highest regulatory exposure)") is the operationally correct first-deployment posture.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    541[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    542[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;191;97;106m-[38;2;191;97;106m [38;2;191;97;106mThe risk profile of this recipe is the highest in Chapter 3 to date. Unlike Recipes 3.1, 3.2, 3.3 (financial-and-operational stakes, no patient-harm path), Recipe 3.4 is in the medication-dispensing path with direct patient-harm consequences (AKI, dialysis, sentinel event, death). The recipe correctly addresses this in the FP/FN asymmetry framing, the alert-fatigue subsection, the regulatory-alignment paragraph naming FDA CDS guidance and DEA controlled-substance requirements, and the disaster-recovery paragraph. The architectural-completeness gaps (A1 idempotency, A2 DLQs, A3 oncology-flag plumbing, A4 cross-reactivity calibration) are the operational backstops that the elevated risk profile warrants. The fairness surface area (S2) is also distinctive: the recipe correctly identifies that medication-dosing models trained on majority populations may flag legitimate dosing for underrepresented populations as anomalous, that pain-management alerts can align with known racial disparities, and that subgroup monitoring is "part of the minimum deployment, not optional"; the architectural artifacts that make this binding rather than aspirational are S2's concern.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    543[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
